{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/nlp-python-pipeline-tutorial-for-text-classification-modeling-6eb1000f909c", "time": 1683006510.080213, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/nlp-python-pipeline-tutorial-for-text-classification-modeling-6eb1000f909c/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "NLP Pipeline Tutorial for Text Classification Modeling | by Matt Przybyla | Towards Data Science", "h1": "NLP Pipeline Tutorial for Text Classification Modeling", "description": "One of the most difficult facets of machine learning is ingesting text data for your model. When building your model, there are your inputs or features, and then what you are trying to predict. While\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://scikit-learn.org/0.19/auto_examples/hetero_feature_union.html", "anchor_text": "sklearn", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://pandas.pydata.org/", "anchor_text": "pandas", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://datascience2.medium.com/subscribe", "anchor_text": "https://datascience2.medium.com/subscribe", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["One of the most difficult facets of machine learning is ingesting text data for your model. When building your model, there are your inputs or features, and then what you are trying to predict. While some types of models can be grouped by either a numerical or categorical predictor or target variable, there is not as much documentation on what to do when you want to use not just numeric, but text as your feature type. Feature transformation is a way to incorporate both types and convert them into a usable format as your X variables to predict your Y predictor or variable. The code below uses sklearn libraries to transform and combine these two types of data into one input.", "NLP, also known as Natural Language Processing, can be used to convert text features into numerical representations. The benefits are listed below:", "The dataset here is randomized, dummy data that has three numerical features; \u2018Confirmed_Test\u2019, \u2018Confirmed_Recovery\u2019, and \u2018Confirmed_New\u2019 with one text feature; \u2018Text_Feature\u2019. The target variable, in this case, is labeled \u2018Text_Predictor\u2019. Normally this dataset would be easily digested into a machine learning model, but here we have a text feature introduced, which does present a problem. The problem is that we have 2 types of data that are very different from one another. Following the tutorial below, this problem is solved and described using Python, sklearn [2] and pandas [3].", "Below is a tutorial on how to set up your Jupyter Notebook .ipynb file or your Python .py file. Using sklearn\u2019s libraries, you can read in your dataframe, transform both the input features and target variable, and then develop a random forest model that helps to predict new labels.", "To follow the tutorial, find a similar dataset that has both numeric and text features with a categorical target variable. First, import your necessary libraries. Reference the sklearn code and classes as well:", "Next, read in your dataframe. Then, create your vec_tdidf object that uses TfidVectorizer by utilizing its term-frequency inverse document frequency vectorizer to transform the count of text into a weighed matrix of term importance. Create a pipeline object using Pipeline to compile the transformer and vectorizer together for the \u2018Text_Feature\u2019. Apply the same rule but to the numeric features instead and label them respectively. Now that all feature types are transformed, use FeatureUnion to combine them all into one.", "The next step is to create your random forest classifier. Then, unite the features together with the classifier and that will be your model object. It is also important to transform your target variable from categorical to numeric using pd.get_dummies.", "Create a list for the text and numeric features and assign your target variable. These new items will be referenced in train_test_split from your dataframe. Next, fit your model using X_train and y_train. Then, you can predict from the test set, X_test.", "Finally, using sklearn metrics, calculate your accuracy_score from your y_test and preds (prediction).", "To summarize, sklearn and its authors, along with pandas, have made it simple to compile messy and heterogeneous data for a clean and efficient input into your machine learning model. Using these common libraries, every data scientist can now not have to just rely on numeric features to predict their target variable but can use text/word/term data as well. With these NLP techniques, a text classification problem such as term categorization can be easily modeled.", "Sidenote \u2014 in my code, text, and files, I use the term \u2018predictor\u2019 as what is predicted, also known as the target variable, or what one is trying to classify.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Sr/MS Data Scientist. Top Writer in Artificial Intelligence, Technology, & Education. Towards Data Science. Subscribe: https://datascience2.medium.com/subscribe"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F6eb1000f909c&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnlp-python-pipeline-tutorial-for-text-classification-modeling-6eb1000f909c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnlp-python-pipeline-tutorial-for-text-classification-modeling-6eb1000f909c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.